evelopment.\\n\\n\\n**Defining Utility Actions**\\n\\nI've transitioned to focusing on utility actions. The goal is to provide enterprise-level utility features within the generated report. Specifically, I'm working on adding instant share, local save, printing, and history management options. The user will be able to export, save, or re-access their report at any point. A clean reset is also being planned.\\n\\n\\n**Designing the Visual Interface**\\n\\nI'm now focusing on the visual metaphor. I envision an \\\"Air-gapped Command Dashboard Terminal\\\" feel, emphasizing secure local storage using browser \\\"disks\\\". I want to incorporate micro-animations like pulsed LEDs, smooth drawers, animated copy icons, and interactive local histories to create a tangible, high-integrity tactical interface. This approach will guide the layout strategy.\\n\\n\\n**Refining UI Elements**\\n\\nI'm now detailing user interface refinements. I've conceived of a \\\"Vault/History\\\" button with a badge for saved blueprint counts. There is a planned privacy notice, presented as an enterprise-grade card to stress that all data is local with no telemetry. I also plan for a \\\"Local History Drawer,\\\" a sliding panel showcasing a timeline of saved blueprints with quick load/delete functions.\\n\\n\\n**Defining Reset Logic**\\n\\nI'm now clarifying the reset behavior. A reset action triggers a full data wipe, returning the user to the starting point. I'm also considering the mobile strategy; I'm planning for floating action buttons to collapse on smaller screens and a full-width sliding drawer. Accessibility is a key focus, ensuring keyboard navigation, tab order, and screen reader compatibility.\\n\\nI'm also specifying which files to change (`BlueprintGenerator.tsx`) and, importantly, which to leave untouched. Finally, I'm defining the `gff_blueprint_history` structure for local storage, including save timestamp, wizard data, score, category, solution title, impact, and dimensions.\\n\\n\\n**Structuring Output Content**\\n\\nI'm now detailing the output content structure to ensure a professional look. I've composed a copy text template for the clipboard, designed to mimic a senior architect's output, with sections for organizational profile, assessments, and the target GFF AI topology, aiming for a high-integrity, structured presentation. The goal is to provide summaries, or provide the data used to create summaries, where we don't need to recalculate.\\n\\n\\n**Refining Print Styling**\\n\\nI'm now integrating print styling. I'm focusing on ensuring clean print outputs, so I'm investigating Tailwind's built-in `print:` utilities for hiding non-printable elements. I'm thinking about how to hide navigation, action buttons, headers, and footers when printing. I also plan to force background colors and optimize text for high contrast. This will integrate cleanly into the current build.\\n\\n\\n\"}}\n93:{\"ts\":\"2026-06-26T17:53:19.204Z\",\"type\":\"agent_event\",\"event\":{\"type\":\"content_start\",\"contentType\":\"tool\",\"toolName\":\"read_files\",\"toolCallId\":\"lm5gso22\",\"input\":{\"files\":[{\"path\":\"/Users/ayushbansal/Documents/GitHub/hirezapp_landing_page/components/sections/BlueprintGenerator.tsx\",\"start_line\":550,\"end_line\":595}]}}}\n","success":true}],"durationMs":21}}
